observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive:
Issue an executive order or internal memorandum for CY 2025 identifying and requiring key employees or department heads to submit a timeline in adopting the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, within 30 days from issuance of such order or memorandum;
Require the municipal accountant and the GSO to maintain separate ledger and property cards and PAR or acquisitions of PPE and conduct regular reconciliation pending the cleansing of the PPE account;
Instruct the inventory committee to perform a comprehensive annual physical count of all PPEs owned by the LGU to ensure accurate records and accountability; and
Require each employee to submit every semester a list of LGU properties under their custody as directed by the Local Chief Executive under Memorandum Order No. 131.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
For transparency and efficiency in the hiring of JOs, make representation with the Sanggunian to enact law standardizing the terms and condition in the hiring and compensation of JO personnel;
Require the Human Resource:
To establish criteria for selection of JO, including renewal procedures, and termination guidelines;
To draft a standard template for JO contracts that clearly outlines the duration of employment, terms and conditions, specific duties and responsibilities, office assignments, and work schedules; and
To ensure that each JO personnel signs the contract before starting work, with a copy provided to the employee.

We recommended the following:
Consider the creation of General Services Office (GSO) separate from the Treasury Department who will be responsible in the preservation, maintenance and safekeeping of the PPEs of the LGU;
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with at least one member each from the Accounting Unit and Supply Unit and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to derecognize properties that do not qualify on the capitalization threshold of PPE and require the Supply Officer to prepare Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for each recorded PPEs that are to be derecognized from PPE account due to capitalization threshold of PPE and ensure that future issuances of semi-expandable properties are issued with ICS and Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) for property and equipment; and
Instruct the GSO to prepare yearly report of inventory of semi-expandable properties in order to monitor existence of the said properties.

Recommendations: 

We have recommended the following:

Find ways to look for sources of fund for the supplemental appropriation of the unpaid electricity expense with a total amount of ₱1,868,817 as of December 31, 2020 in order to stop the agency’s practice of charging prior years’ expenditure to current year appropriation;

Enjoin the Municipal Budget Officer to strictly follow budget procedure and ensure that utility expenses are automatically included in the yearly budget appropriation;

Require the Municipal Accountant to take up in the books expenditures and obligations incurred during the current period so as to reflect the correct pertinent account in the financial statements;

Ensure that electricity bills are paid on time to avoid incurrence of surcharge, otherwise officials and employees responsible for the delay shall be personally liable for any disallowance;

Enjoin the Municipal Treasurer to strictly implement the collection policy of electric bills due to the stall lessees; and



Consider the idea of separate electric meter for every stall in the BCC and Public Market by incorporating the same in the Lease Agreement to ease the burden on the part of the Municipality from the delinquent lessees.

